..TEXT:
The precise Virgilian text that lies behind Dante's
generically 'Virgilian' opening flourish is debated.  Major candidates
include ^Aen~. III.147, ^Aen~. IV.522-528, ^Aen~. VIII.26-27 (favored
by perhaps a majority), ^Aen~. IX.224-225, ^Geo~. I.427-428.  See
discussion in Mazzoni,  ^Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina
Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III~ (Florence: Sansoni, 1967),  pp.
165-166.  These three lines, as has often been noted, have a sad
eloquence that establishes a mode of writing to which the poet will
return when he considers the Virgilian 'tears of things' in the lives
of some of his characters.
