..TEXT:
Padoan (comm. to ^Inf~. II.15) points out that the insistence
on the physicality of Aeneas's descent effectively undercuts that
tradition of medieval allegorized Virgil which asserts that the
'descent' is to be taken as a 'philosophical,' rather than as a
literal, journey.  Aeneas' journey, like Dante's own, is to be dealt
with as actually having occurred in space and time.
