..TEXT:
Barbi (^Problemi di critica dantesca~ [Florence: Sansoni,
1934]), p. 237, argues for the view, advanced by S. Betti a century
ago, that 'maggiore,' in early Italian, was a title of honor ('the
great'), a positive form of the adjective, not its comparative form
('greater').  Mazzoni (^Saggio di un nuovo commento alla "Divina
Commedia": "Inferno" --Canti I-III~ [Florence: Sansoni, 1967]), pp.
220-22, supports this thesis, but also represents those who do argue
for the comparative sense of the adjective here, believing that it
refers to the fact that Peter, the first pope, was 'greater' than all
his successors.
