EN-A10-O2-L92 A10-O2-L92
EN-A10-O2-L93 A10-O2-L93
..TEXT:
Beatrice's insistence that she is not 'touchable' by the
grim powers of the pains of hell underlines the marginality of sin for
the saved.  Hell is simply not of concern to them.  It is important to
know, as one begins reading the poem, what one can only know once one
has finished it: no soul in purgation or in grace in heaven has a
thought for the damned (only the damned themselves do).  Their concern
for those who do not share their redeeming penitence or bliss is
reserved for those still alive on earth, who have at least the hope of
salvation.  Hell, for the saved, is a sordid reality of which it is
better not to speak.  A similar disregard for the damned (and even for
our mortal hero, wrestling with his sins) is evidenced by the wryly
laconic and unsympathetic angel who descends to help Virgil lead his
charge into the City of Dis (^Inf~. IX.91-103).  Those who admire
various of Dante's sinners, despite their eternal damnation, would do
well to keep both these scenes in mind.  See the strong statements to
this effect found in Grandgent&#8219;s article "^Quid Ploras~," ^Dante
Studies~ 118 (2000 [1926]), pp. 85-94; Grandgent reminds his reader of
the harsh question put by the angel to St. Paul, who has allowed
himself to weep for the damned, in the apocryphal ^Visio Pauli~.  The
angel wants to know why Paul is weeping ("Quid ploras?") for the damned
when his attention should be turned to Christ.
