..TEXT:
Beatrice concludes her speech by expressing the efficacy
of Lucy's words on Dante's behalf, which won her over to interceding
with Virgil in order to give her beloved a second chance.
(^Purgatorio~ XXX and XXXI will reveal that she had grounds for being
less charitable to her backsliding lover.)  Her speech concludes with
the same sort of ^captatio benevolentiae~ that marked its inception
(^Inf~. II.58 and the note to ^Inf~. II.58), now couched in terms that
praise Virgil's ^parlare onesto~.  The phrase means more than 'honest
speech,' as is made clear by its etymological propinquity to the verb
^onora~ (honors) in the next line.  'Noble' (found also in Sinclair's
translation) seemed to the translators a reasonable way to attempt to
bridge the gap between 'honest' and 'decorous,' retaining a sense of
moral and stylistic gravity for the words
of the greatest poet of pagan antiquity -- which Virgil was for Dante.
