..TEXT:
Beatrice's tears may remind a reader of Venus's when the
goddess weeps for her burdened son in ^Aeneid~ I.228, as was perhaps
first suggested by Hollander, ^Allegory in Dante&#8219;s "Commedia,"~
pp. 91-92.  See also Jacoff, "The Tears of Beatrice," ^Dante Studies~
100 (1982), p. 3, showing that the verse probably reflects Rachel's
tears for her lost children (Jeremiah 31:15) -- who are eventually
restored to her (as will Dante be to Beatrice).
